'''March 23''' is the 23rd day of the month {{ill|March (Lunisolar)|ja|3月 (旧暦)|lt=March (Yayoi)|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/March (Lunisolar)|qq=}}, the 3rd month of the traditional {{ill|Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|ja|旧暦|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|11=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|qq=}}. Its {{ill|Rokuyō|ja|六曜|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rokuyō|qq=}} day is {{ill|Senshū|qid=Q96759839|1=senshū}}{{efn|ja|先勝|1=Rokuyō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q9418169}}{{efn|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senshō|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 六曜|1=Rokuyō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q9418169}}.

== Events ==
* [[Reki-nin]] 1st year ({{ill|Julian calendar|en|Julian calendar|qid=Q11184|lt=Julian calendar|1=Julian calendar}} {{ill|1238|en|1238|qid=Q5433|lt=1238|1=1238}} {{ill|May 8|en|May 8|qid=Q2555|lt=May 8|1=May 8}}) – The monk Jōkō began the construction of the great Buddha at Kōtoku-ji in Kamakura (the Kamakura Daibutsu).
* {{ill|Kangen|en|Kangen|qid=Q1194187|lt=Kangen|1=Kangen}} 4th year ({{ill|Julian calendar|en|Julian calendar|qid=Q11184|lt=Julian calendar|1=Julian calendar}} {{ill|1246|en|1246|qid=Q5441|lt=1246|1=1246}} {{ill|April 10|en|April 10|qid=Q2502|lt=April 10|1=April 10}}) – The Kamakura shogunate’s Shikken, {{ill|Hōjō Tokiyori|en|Hōjō Tokiyori|qid=Q1354410|lt=Hojo Tokiyori|1=Hōjō Tokiyori}}, due to severe illness, was succeeded by his younger brother as the 5th Shikken.
* {{ill|Kan'ei|en|Kan'ei|qid=Q1192913|lt=Kan'ei|1=Kan'ei}} 10th year ({{ill|Gregorian calendar|en|Gregorian calendar|qid=Q12138|lt=Gregorian calendar|1=Gregorian calendar}} {{ill|1633|en|1633|qid=Q6870|lt=1633|1=1633}} {{ill|May 1|en|May 1|qid=Q2544|lt=May 1|1=May 1}}) – The shogunate under 【征夷大将軍】 {{ill|Tokugawa Iemitsu|en|Tokugawa Iemitsu|qid=Q314481|lt=Tokugawa Iemitsu|1=Tokugawa Iemitsu}} instructed his close aides, including {{ill|Matsudaira Nobutsuna|en|Matsudaira Nobutsuna|qid=Q6788056|lt=Matsudaira Nobutsuna|1=Matsudaira Nobutsuna}}, to deliberate and decide on minor matters, laying the foundation for the office of the {{ill|Wakadoshiyori|en|Wakadoshiyori|qid=Q1036547|lt=Wakadoshiyori|1=Wakadoshiyori}}.
* {{ill|Ansei|en|Ansei|qid=Q1327259|lt=Ansei|1=Ansei}} 1st year ({{ill|Gregorian calendar|en|Gregorian calendar|qid=Q12138|lt=Gregorian calendar|1=Gregorian calendar}} {{ill|1854|en|1854|qid=Q7670|lt=1854|1=1854}} {{ill|April 20|en|April 20|qid=Q2524|lt=April 20|1=April 20}}) – The Russian envoy, Puchachin, visited Nagasaki for a second time following his previous arrival.
== Births ==
* {{ill|Tenpō|en|Tenpō|qid=Q1369045|lt=Tenpō|1=Tenpō}} 12nd year ({{ill|Gregorian calendar|en|Gregorian calendar|qid=Q12138|lt=Gregorian calendar|1=Gregorian calendar}} {{ill|1841|en|1841|qid=Q7622|lt=1841|1=1841}} {{ill|May 13|en|May 13|qid=Q2560|lt=May 13|1=May 13}}) – {{ill|Fukuchi Ō Sakurachi|ja|福地桜痴|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukuchi Ō Sakurachi|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 福地源一郎|1=Fukuchi Gen'ichirō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q861241}} (Fukuchi Genichirō), a journalist and playwright (died {{ill|1906|en|1906|qid=Q2049|lt=1906|1=1906}}).
== Deaths ==

== Commemorations ==
* [[Mazu Tan]] – Also known as {{ill|Tin Hau (disambiguation)|en|Tin Hau (disambiguation)|qid=Q1305664|lt=Tianhou|1=Tin Hau (disambiguation)}}, commemorating the birth of the sea goddess Mazu who protects fishermen and seafarers. Mazu is believed to have been born during the Song Dynasty in Fujian; large festivals are held at Mazu and Tianhou temples throughout Fujian, Taiwan, Guangdong, Hong Kong, and Macau.

